# Phase A: Standard Library & Multi-file Compilation

To make Englist usable and provide `std.math`, `std.string`, `std.collections`, `std.io`, `std.fs`, `std.net`, `std.time`, `std.random`, `std.json`, and `std.concurrent`, we must significantly expand the compiler's capabilities. A standard library requires the ability to split code across multiple files, bind to native C functions (FFI) for OS interactions, and define complex data structures (Generics/Classes).

## User Review Required

> [!WARNING]
> This phase requires introducing multi-file compilation and native C bindings (`foreign` functions). The standard library will be written purely in Englist where possible, and bound to libc/LLVM via `foreign function` where OS interaction is needed. Are you okay with the standard library being distributed alongside the compiler in a `lib/std` directory?

## Open Questions
- **Generics**: Should we formalize generics directly via `TypeExpr::Generic` (e.g., `List of number`) in the type checker, or rely on runtime polymorphism (void pointers) for this phase? 
- **Object Methods**: Englist has `AstItem::Type` (Structs) but no explicit method declarations yet (though `target_type` exists on `FunctionDef`). Should methods be declared simply as functions targeting a type? (e.g., `function add(number val) on Vector`)

## Proposed Changes

---

### CLI & Module Resolution

We will introduce multi-file compilation.
#### [MODIFY] [eng-cli/src/main.rs](file:///Users/babayaga/englist/crates/eng-cli/src/main.rs)
- Refactor the compilation pipeline to handle a `Workspace` instead of a single file.
- Scan for `Use(UseDecl)` in the AST. 
- Resolve `use std.math` to `$ENGLIST_ROOT/lib/std/math.eng`.
- Merge imported AST items into the central module before Type Checking.

---

### Foreign Function Interface (FFI)

To do file I/O, sockets, and threads, we need native C bindings. The lexer already has a `Foreign` token, but the parser ignores it.
#### [MODIFY] [eng-parser/src/parser.rs](file:///Users/babayaga/englist/crates/eng-parser/src/parser.rs)
- Parse `foreign function open(text path) returns number`.
- Store `is_foreign` on `FunctionDef`.

#### [MODIFY] [eng-hir/src/ast.rs](file:///Users/babayaga/englist/crates/eng-hir/src/ast.rs) & [eng-mir/src/lib.rs](file:///Users/babayaga/englist/crates/eng-mir/src/lib.rs)
- Propagate `is_foreign` through HIR and MIR.

#### [MODIFY] [eng-llvm/src/codegen.rs](file:///Users/babayaga/englist/crates/eng-llvm/src/codegen.rs)
- For `foreign` functions, skip generating a block/body and emit a `module.add_function()` declaration to bind dynamically at link time.

---

### Type Checking & Generics (Foundation)

To support `Vector` and `HashMap`, we need basic structural type lowering.
#### [MODIFY] [eng-types/src/type_pass.rs](file:///Users/babayaga/englist/crates/eng-types/src/type_pass.rs)
- Formalize `infer_type_def` to properly lower struct definitions and fields.
- Tie `target_type` (methods) to the struct.
- Wire `TypeExpr::List` and `TypeExpr::Dict` to the standard library implementations of Vector/HashMap.

---

### Standard Library Files

We will create a standard library written in Englist.
#### [NEW] [lib/std/io.eng](file:///Users/babayaga/englist/lib/std/io.eng)
- Provide FFI bindings for `printf` and wrappers for standard I/O.
#### [NEW] [lib/std/fs.eng](file:///Users/babayaga/englist/lib/std/fs.eng)
- Provide FFI bindings for `fopen`, `fread`, `fwrite`, `fclose`.
#### [NEW] [lib/std/collections.eng](file:///Users/babayaga/englist/lib/std/collections.eng)
- Provide implementations for `Vector` (dynamic array wrapper over malloc/realloc) and `HashMap`.
#### [NEW] [lib/std/math.eng](file:///Users/babayaga/englist/lib/std/math.eng)
- Basic math utilities and `foreign` bindings for `pow`, `sin`, `cos`.
#### [NEW] [lib/std/net.eng](file:///Users/babayaga/englist/lib/std/net.eng)
- Sockets wrapping standard POSIX C socket libraries.

## Verification Plan

### Automated Tests
- `cargo test` across all crates to ensure parser and compiler stability.

### Manual Verification
- Write a test Englist script `test_std.eng` that does `use std.fs`, opens a file, writes to it, reads from it, and pushes items into a `Vector`.
- Compile and execute the native binary to confirm standard library integration and OS interaction works as expected.